review_blob: Pours slightly hazy copper with huge head. Aroma is sour, fruity, inviting. Refreshing on the palate, the sourness is not as extreme as the nose suggests. Distinct milky note. Very easy drinking, more please.
Pours cloudy golden with quote a bit of sediment. Sweet funky aroma, huge head. This might have been standing for a bit too long, as the flavour was sweet and yeasty, unbalanced.
Pours dark copper with no head. Sour cherry & malt aroma. Pleasantly sour cherry flavour. Oily mouthfeel with a slightly bitter aftertaste. Not very complex, but I could drink this all. Day. Long.

75cl bottle bought at the old school and stored in my cellar for 3 years. Pours dark coffee brown with almost no head; very little carbonation. Heavy burnt caramel aroma. Quite pronounced bitterness in the flavour, giving way to a sweet coffee aftertaste. Not my favourite stout, but of course a good showing from de Molen.

75cl bottle bought at Brassigaume out the back of the brewers van ... ;)

Pours light golden with quite a lot of sediment. Aroma is initially quite powerfully sour. The flavour is sour funk with a rather hoppy bitterness in the aftertaste. Very nice saison.

25cl bottle, 2007 vintage, Q56821. I dont even remember where I bought this - it has followed me through two moves. Today I poured a brown, almost non-carbonated liquid into an Orval glass and enjoyed the raisin and wood aroma mixing with the tones of some funky jazz. The mouthfeel is smooth and oily, the flavour is so thick you can chew it. Theres raisin, toffee, chocolate, yorkshire pie, a bit of burn, figs, coffee, beef, and a rainy English autumn day. All poured into this minute bottle.

This is as close to perfection as you can get. Can I have a crate?
Pours cloudy golden with a small head. Aroma is peat and hay. Flavour is a rather attractive mixture of peat and hops. I quite like this.

75cl bottle bought at Brassigaume [out the back of the brewers van ... ;) ]. Pours initially golden with a massive head. As the head quickly settles and becomes denser, the beer darkens to copper. Aroma is funky with sweet hops, honey. Flavour is sweet, hoppy, biting, soothing. Very nice beer. One more please!
Pours golden with medium head. Fresh, non-deScript flavour. Not bad, just kinda meh.
Pours coffee black with little to no head. Burnt coffee aroma. Fairly full mouthfeel, surprisingly good schwarzbier. Almost porter-like.
Pleasant, not too hoppy IPA. Doesnt hold a candle to the American versions; this is clearly intended for the German palate. Not bad, not too exciting either.

Bottle bought in Lidl, Vimperk. Pours black with cappuccino coloured head. Caramel, malt aroma. Fairly rough coffee flavour - much more tauo than expected, but not easy drinking. Better than expected.
At a cafe in Passau. Cloudy brown net with small head. Sweet aroma, yeast and caramel. Sweet and refreshing flavour, not very strong but well made beer.

On tap at a small Czech ski hut. Comes caramel brown with a decent sized foam crown. Malty aroma. Pleasant caramel flavour with moderate bitterness. Tendency to metallic aftertaste as it warms, but a very decent session beer.
I had this a week ago and didnt get around to take notes on it, so Ive forgotten all about it. Must have been utterly inoffensive and forgettable.
Pretty decent beer from Svaneke Bryghus. Dont care too much for the M&R; branding, though.
I had this yesterday and Ive already forgotten what it was like. I guess that means it was pretty average ... went well with chili.
Pours cloudy copper with thin head. Floral, grassy aroma. Sweet flavour, hops not forward. Pleasant enough ale to go with a curry.
Pours golden with a bubbly head. Sweet, hoppy aroma. Very pleasant flavour, easy-drinking session beer.
Pours cloudy with a decent amount of foam. Sweet, bready flavour. Average weizen.
Pours cloudy golden with dense but thin head. Crisp bitter aroma, extremely bitter flavour. Well made but ultimately too much for me.

Pours orangey golden with a big head that quickly collapses to a more managable finger-wide sagging foam crown. Undefined bittersweet aroma, while the flavour is more sweet from the honey with nice hops. However, the intense carbonation makes it hard to enjoy the beer.
Pours cloudy copper with just small, thin islands of foam on top. No carbonation at all in the very sweet liquid. Poor excuse for a craft beer.

Pours black with cream coffee coloured head. Malty sour aroma. As the beer warms, the flavour goes from generic sweet stout to a very acidic oak / burnt caramel flavour. There are many good stouts out there - this isnt one of them.
Pours slightly cloudy golden colour. Fresh, floral aroma and a pleasant hoppiness in the flavour. Good, easy-drinking but not exceptional.

On tap at the Brazen Head. Pours dark brown with a small, slightly off-white head. Watery and slightly less tasty than regular Guinness. While the beer isnt actually bad, its still one of the worst porters Ive tried.
Pours blackish brown with small head. Sweet malty aroma. Sweet flavour with some roasted notes, but watery and not powerful enough for my liking. The alleged coconut is not discernible.
Pours golden with medium head. Floral hop aroma. Pleasant bitterness, a very easy drinking beer. Not bad at all.
Pours light brown with thin head. Malt coconut aroma. Slightly hoppy, coconut flavour. Coconut everywhere. Weird.
Pours medium yellow with small head. Indistinct aroma, uninteresting taste. The weakest Kinnegar Ive had so far.
Pours reddish copper with light beige head. Aroma is indistinct. Flavour is good, with balanced hops. Quite pleasant.
Pours slightly cloudy with a fairly solid head. Clear hoppy aroma and a crisp bitterness. Not bad, but not exactly a session beer.
Pours a dark, slightly cloudy copper with a dense head. Crisp, bitter aroma. Floral bitterness but a very dry aftertaste. Not bad, but very hopped.
Pours opaque dark brown with a healthy latte-coloured foam crown. Burnt coffee aroma. Coffee, caramel, vanilla, oak flavours. Excellent stout.

Pours clear golden with small head. Sweet aroma. The flavour straight out of the fridge is pleasantly hopyy and bitter, but as the beer warms just a little, a wet cardboard taste permeates the brew. Uh. Average, I guess.
Decent, but still a rather average APA. Look to Riegele for a better German take on this style.
Sampled @ Brassigaume 2014. More sour than the Quetsche, still a pleasant gueuze packing quite a punch. Very good.
Sampled @ Brassigaume 2014. Pours a totally opaque apricot colour. Fruity sour aroma. Rather wonderful sweet-sour flavour. Very nice.
Pours copper with decent, pillowy head. Floral aroma. Nice fruity flavour that gives way to a well-balanced bitterness. Quite good!
On tap at LEstaminet, Verdun. Didnt leave a lasting impression, but it wasnt too bad.
Almost opaque reddish brown with finger-thick pink foam crown. Sweet aroma and sweet, sweet lemonade flavour. Good for people who want to get drunk quickly.
On tap at LEstaminet, Verdun, and served in a gimmick cone glass. Slightly cloudy golden colour, dense but thin white head. Sweet aroma, standard blonde malt flavour. Average but not bad.

beer_brewer_name: Brouwerij der Trappistenabdij De Achelse Kluis
review_blob: Pours a deep, cloudy golden colour with a dense head. Floral aroma. Initial mouthfeel is somewhat "spritzig" and sharp but quickly gives way to a pleasantly warming flavour. Good.
Bottle labeled "herstbock" bought at the museum. Pours dark brown with minimal head. Malty aroma. Pleasant enough flavour but somewhat watery mouthfeel. Average.
Pours dark reddish brown with little foam. Intense malt, raisin and coffee aroma. Powerful flavour with good hops. Excellent.
Sampled at the museum. Looks like a witbier, but with a malty aroma and a sharp flavour. Not bad, but slightly weird.

"Not your traditional brown ale" - I daresay, this is more like a coffee porter. Pours dark brown with massive head. Burnt coffee aroma. Coffee, malts, caramel sugar gives way to a burnt flavour in the back of my mouth. Very forward. Interesting, but somewhat unbalanced.
Pours golden with medium head, quickly disappearing. Sweet malt aroma. Inoffensive, sweet but somewhat boring flavour. Indistinctive.
Pours reddish brown with minimal head. Sweet toffee and raisin flavour, that appears again in the smooth flavour. Very nice ale.

33cl bottle from P&M;, two months past BB date. Pours dark brown with crema head. Lots of unappetizing light brown sediment. Sour coffee roast aroma. Burnt malt, syrup and coffee flavour, good with a sharp bitter aftertaste.
